Every morning, you will see at least one dog waste on your way to the train station, or on your way to the supermarket. My biggest pet peeve is dog waste on the floor everywhere I go in this neighborhood. Be careful and keep your shoes clean!
The first thing you have to understand about Portland, Oregon is the definition of "weird". The unofficial town slogan, on the back of a building that serves as a pizza joint, bar, music venue, strip club, and skirts the law on at least half of these endeavors, is "Keep Portland Weird". To some, this is a small cry to remember the Portland of the 90's and early 2000's, a Portland that was less known and less expensive, generating creative and unique subcultures. To others, it is a beckoning call - come to Portland, where people will still call you weird, but as a compliment this time. Despite the influx of affluent Californians and the constant construction of condominiums to house these Californians, Portland is still weird. Weird does not mean always accepting, but it does mean accepting of things that are normally not accepted. Weird does not mean we do not have modern conveniences and modern fights. Like the rest of the country, we buy most of our things from China. There are a million ways of being weird, of being not normal, but Portland has plenty of normal. Portland has yoga and hipsters and business professionals. Perhaps weird means we just take all of this less seriously. In my neighborhood, as in many Portland neighborhoods, we have colorful houses, home gardens with flowers and herbs and vegetables lining the streets, and free boxes in the summertime. Free boxes are traditionally cardboard boxes containing items someone is getting rid of, but they can be plastic bags or boxes. They contain something magical, a treasure just perfect for the person wandering by, a surprising amount of the time. Free boxes tend to have clothes and books, but they can have anything. The magical potential of walking through a Southeast Portland neighborhood is what Portland is all about. That is, what Portland is all about to me, but I am just one variety of weird among thousands. Some people I live among would never dream of picking their clothes out of a box on the sidewalk. Those people go to goat yoga (yes, yoga with real live goats) or Timbers matches (the city's soccer team). Portland is full of people who love all sorts of things. Portland is full of people who pursue our dreams, or dream about pursuing our dreams while spending too much time at the bar. Yes, Portland has a drug problem. Drug problems tend to be (at their root) mental health problems, and the constant rain through much of the year, plus the dreary clouds, appear to be a contributor. Portland has a homelessness problem too, which no one seems to know what to do with. The homeless population is drawn by the social services Portland offers, better than in most parts of the country, but our services are insufficient, as in all parts of the country. The non-homeless population wavers between care and hatred. In this, we are not weird at all.
The mountains are always there. In the north, bearing witness to the sun’s journey every dawn and every dusk. No matter how much I forget about them or how caught up with work and life I am to notice, they are there, unwavering, unopposed, and unphased by life’s tribulations. Then on days when I am the most stressed and wound, they demand to be seen, and when I turn to them they let me rest my anxious soul, lending me some strength to go on, one day at a time. I first moved here when I started my undergrad, and the mountains to the north of campus where what first captivated me. Sure, the university has its own share of breathtaking sights in buildings and ponds and trees, which have their own share of my heart, but it’s the mountains that really holds its throne. The rest of the town is beautiful in its own right. There are countless cafés that were home to many hours of caffeine fueled cramming. One can walk or take the bus just a little further to the downtown area and be enveloped in an aura of antiquity by the faded colored bricks that line restaurants and office buildings. It is here that this seemingly suburban town shows as much bustle and vigor as it’s neighboring urban city. This doesn’t last for many blocks though, as one can escape, once again, to the serene small town by passing the library. This dichotomy of atmospheres in such proximity truly give this city a wonderous vibe as if it was beckoning to be explored. With this, it is easy to create many a cherished memory, each in association with a certain part of town. Whether it is walking past the rusted swings in the park with friends after an all-nighter or running through the busy downtown to catch the movie in the fancy theater for which the university provided tickets. Alas, it is also home to many harsh memories, as all places are bound to be in life. The ponds, in particular, can be a rather fitting place for reflection as well as crying sessions at two in the morning in the middle of an existential crisis. The latter of which, I have more experience in. While watching the turtles and ducks and insects live out their lives, each with some contribution or role, I couldn’t help but wonder about my own sense of purpose as I struggled to navigate this mystery called life. So, I walked past the pond, and past the park and little houses that scream of suburbia, until I reached a main street. It was then that sun shined its brilliant rays atop the palm trees, painting the sky along the way, and as I looked up at the sunrise, I realized I was walking north. Sure enough, they were there, as they had always been. The sturdy overbearing mountains grazed the hazy blue and yellow sky more than any building in the horizon, and as if speaking without words, stirred in me my sense of perseverance.
You might pass it up on first glance - after all, it is a residential area behind a shopping strip, not a place one would assume there are places to live. At least, not places most people would want to live. But if you go behind the old, abandoned Whole Foods and walk back behind the hotels which are only occupied annually aside from a few stints in the summertime for family reunions, you'll find an entire bustling community. Within these communities, on these streets, are a handful of apartment complex - situated next to each other carefully like Russian nesting dolls that have been scrupulously, carefully taken apart and set beside each other in a line down the road, piecemeal. The first apartments you come upon are ones which have been on the news for some fairly unsavory dealings, so we won't focus on those too much - appearances, after all, can be deceiving. But the apartments beside that complex, and the two complexes beside that one, are a whole other world that almost no one living in this area knows about. Across from those complexes is a community college's satellite campus - a quiet, sleepy set of buildings standing sentinel beside the road, where students putter in with coffee in hand, yawning at 7 in the morning to begin their sleepy days. The iron gates creak open to admit them one by one, while commuters shake their fists out the window and groan at them for holding up traffic on days attendance is higher. The road t-bones into another residential road, with a park on one side and a rehabilitation center for people who have broken bones in unfortunate circumstances. The treatment center boasts cheerful porch furniture, and a lazily undulating ceiling fan which churns the warm, thick summertime air back and forth. Children run back and forth in the grass at the park across the street, cartwheeling and pinwheeling across the prickly green stalks while bees lazily turn in the flower patches by the road. Old retired folks walk their dogs on the walking path, scowling at the teenagers on their skateboards and nodding demurely at the teenage girls clustered by the playground equipment, gossiping about boys and the latest YouTube sensations. There is a sushi place in a strip mall beside the park that has inexpensive food but never seems too busy - a swimming supply store right beside that, and a nail salon nestled in between. You could fill your pool for the season while getting a manicure and eating hibachi chicken, all at once - the beauty of a strip mall. There is a frozen yogurt place there too, one of the DIY kind, and you often see the teens in the park clutching cold, sweating cups of frozen yogurt covered in toppings while they do stunts on their skateboards and vape because they believe it to be the coolest. The neighborhood in question is a slice of Americana - a piece of history in the sleepy south where hardly anything changes, not even time.
My neighborhood is interesting. Most of the houses are single family, but there are a few homes that have been split into two, while still being attached, if that makes much sense. My home has a small yard in front of it and a small driveway to the left of the house. It, like most of the others, reminds you of a time not so long ago where living in the suburbs was the American dream. This dream at once seemed to embrace the people of this country, but now its pulling away. But my neighborhood and many more still remain, still call out to us and those who visit that the dream is still alive, and we are still holding onto it as best we can. The people don't feel as optomistic as they used to, the upkeep of the little yards are not what they used to be, but there is still a car or two in every driveway, still the youth play as if the world around them was the whole of their existence. The public school that has been here for almost 90 years still stands, still seems conjure a future in today's youth, while stirring up nostalgia in the older residents. The churches are few and far between, mostly empty, but the basketball courts are still full. All of the homes look different, but feel the same. There is a large supermarket called super "A" that has been owned by a large Yemni family, who are quite possible the only Arab family in the neighborhood. The vast majority of the residents are African American. The streets are wide and the kids usually play footbal, only stopping to allow the cars to pass. Most of the people in my neighborhood have been here for generations and most can tell stories of a past where everyone knew everyone. There was a karate school, but when hollywood stopped making karate kid movies, the kids stopped wanting to be the karate kid, so its now a pharmacy, because drugs make everything better, or so I've heard. There is also a small movie theatre that plays old movies at a discounted price, spared from the crowds by the youth's disdane for its lack of just release titles, but favored by the elders, who think it is a small price to pay for a night out, without the kids of course. There is a single expressway that passes through my town. Though the exit and entrance are in the town next to ours. There was once a petition to get and exit for our town. The youth supported it, while the elders refused. It seems that having the expressway in our town would ruin it, so said the elders who eventually persuaded the city council to deny the request. They are building a new highschool, and we are trying to decide on a mascott for our town. I think a cyborg with a country accent and a log cabin would be then best representation of my town.
Since I live in a large city, my neighborhood is extremely diverse. Residential areas are dispersed, seemingly randomly, between commercial areas, where a variety of businesses are run. Some of these businesses are made up of offices, while others are various stores, restaurants, and places of entertainment. There is no shortage of new restaurants to eat at, or stores to shop in. While some stores are large, well-known, brands that are owned by large corporations, small boutiques are also increasingly popular. They are not only located in various malls, but they also line the streets, which are often in walking distance of neighborhoods that would otherwise be quiet and serene, if not surrounded by so many points of interest. There are also a couple of nearby parks, and I have noticed that people frequent these parks with their young children. Speaking of the people, thereâ€™s actually quite a bit of diversity within my neighborhood. In one small location, we have a prominent LGBTQ+ community, an Orthodox Jewish community, and a collection of refugees and immigrants from the former Soviet Union. Spanning a little further outside of my neighborhood, there are many more individuals of various races and origins, although they are sometimes broken up into their own little communities within the city. We have locations known as Korea town, China town, Little Armenia, and many more, which are only a few miles away. However, only a few miles can prove to be a very lengthy drive. Driving a distance of only 10 miles can sometimes span two hours, due to traffic, especially during rush hour. Hardly anyone in my city walks anywhere, though. While certain locations of interest are inevitably close-by, the city is huge, and people do not generally prefer to commute on foot. As a result, we also have some of the worst traffic in the world, and it can be difficult to find parking spots just about anywhere. Ironically enough, there has been a great deal of construction in recent years, as large apartment buildings are being added to the city. It is seems to be a popular destination, but many residents are disappointed by the prospect of even more people moving in, and even more vehicles on the roads. There are many different types of houses in my city, however. Not everyone lives, or wishes to live, in a large apartment building. Residential areas are made up of houses, of various sizes, and smaller apartment buildings and condominiums. Some properties contain single-family homes, while others contain duplexes. This is true even within my immediately neighborhood, so there is also no lack of diversity in regards to housing options. Similarly, the neighborhood is made up of people of varying ages, and to be perfectly honest, I am not familiar with the majority of my neighbors. It is not really a tight-knit community these days, although I have many memories from my childhood of playing outside with my next-door neighbor, and a few other friends from the neighborhood, who were all close to my age.
“Where is everything?” she asked as we drove past the corn fields which filled the horizon. “This is it!” I said, knowing she’d be in shock of the sparseness of the open landscape. She was from a town in which the grocery store was a 5 minute walk from her house--she’d never seen this much open space in her life. Taken back by the ubiquity of corn fields, I shared with her what it was like to grow up in rural Ohio, and in that moment, she finally knew who I was and where I came from. Driving down a two-lane country road, you will reach a quarry which is filled with water. Just past it is the small development I live in. The houses are mostly composed of brick and stucco. All the houses have at least a half an acre of land to themselves which everyone takes pride in maintaining. During springtime, annually planted flowers are abundant along with the midwestern trees that change with every season. The driveways are all filled with the highest end Mercedes Benz luxury cars that glisten in the midday sun after a good, old-fashioned car wash. Continuing along the road toward my grey stucco home, my Korean neighbor is always outside with a friendly face. He tends to spend the entire day mowing his lawn and can be heard singing over his mower’s hum. Everyone in the neighborhood gets a laugh out of him, but he is always genuine and an amazing person with a unique history. He has grown older and has lost some of his wit as he aged. In his past he was a doctor and usually blends in with the grass and his John Deer Zero Turn mower. Finally, you will reach my home. In the side yard, geese are abundant and are chased by our Terrier. Out back, there is a small stream that feeds into the quarry. Here, you can hear bullfrogs, the stream, and the occasional “moo” from the nearby farms. Across the handmade wooden bridge is an untouched oasis filled with naturally growing trees, herbs, and wildflowers. Here was where I spent most of my childhood. From building tree forts to ‘hunting’ animals (which mostly consisted of chasing them), there was always something to do and usually a neighborhood child available for friendship. The winters in my small town can be painfully brutal, yet there is nothing more beautiful. The yard transforms from a sea of green into an empty wilderness. The trees that once housed vibrant pink, purple, and orange flowers turn into barren skeletons of bark. When blessed with the occasional snowfall, a winter wonderland appears overnight. The backyard is lined with snow angels made by my little sister, and snowmen. My sister and I fought frequently as kids, and during the winter, snowballs were our weapon of choice. We’d build massive igloo-like forts to house our weapons, usually with branches, like an arsenal. In our own little wonderland was where we played pretend during a time where nothing else mattered. We were just young kids without a care in the world.
transformed_texts:
I live in a small town in Michigan, in Rural America. Here, farmland leads to small tourist cities. There are no big city malls, no Wal-Mart, Target, or Applebee’s. You have to drive to reach places. But, I live in one of the most beautiful places, with water all around. My town has water on both sides. Lake Michigan is on one side, and Lake Charlevoix is on the other. You can find a beach everywhere you go.

My neighborhood is like a small town. Houses are not close together. They are not all the same. Some houses are old, some are updated. Most have full basements you can see from the road. Many houses have older aluminum siding. There are houses in many colors around my house. Most houses have yards. Yards have trampolines and playsets. Some people have gardens and fences for pets. Houses look like Middle America. People work hard and raise families here.

You see kids running on the streets. People walk dogs, bike, and rollerblade. Neighbors know each other. You know who belongs and who does not. You wave at someone grilling outside or smile at a person walking their dog. Lawns are in good condition. Leaves are not piled up. Grass is green and cut. Plants and bushes are trimmed. It is not a fancy neighborhood, but it is a good place to raise a family. It is quiet, peaceful, and safe. It looks average but is special because it is a safe place to come home to. 

Close by, there is the county sheriff’s department and a jail. The Health Department is next to it. The city recycling center is down the road. Neighbors use these services. We have baseball and softball fields nearby. You can hear the announcers. The small town airport is next to the fields. You hear small planes take off and land. You can walk to get ice cream. Downtown is close by. My kids can ride bikes to the park, which is about eight blocks away. It is a great place to live.

I live in a typical suburb. My neighborhood has a homeowner's association. When you enter, you see well-kept homes. The front yards are alike. There is grass, pebbles, and short driveways. Sometimes you see small trees. Every house has a two-car garage. The roads are new and smooth. There are no potholes. Most houses are one story, but some have two. We do not have mailboxes in front of each house. Instead, there is a group of mailboxes at the street's end. Each person uses a key to open their mailbox. There are two big lockers for packages. The homeowner's association likes everything to look the same. My house is on the edge of the city. So, my neighborhood is part rural and part suburban. We have a lot of land. There are many community pools. They are well-kept and have gates. There are walking trails too. You can walk your dog or go for a walk. You can run around the neighborhood for exercise. Most people here are retired. It is a safe area. People look out for each other. There are also some middle-aged and young professionals. The city is large by population but feels small. We have most things you need. We have one mall. It is not big, but it is enough. It takes about 15 minutes to drive to important places. There are many stores to choose from. We have grocery stores with organic food. We also have bargain outlets with few items and few staff. My neighborhood is safe and well-kept. We have nice things like pools and trails. We are not close to shopping, but you can drive to any big store you like.

The first time I heard about my place was on a podcast. The podcast talked about people who went missing. It was a surprise to me. Almost every apartment here costs over a thousand dollars each month. I never heard about that story. My friends did not know about it either. Maybe it is hard here. Some friends cry at night. Things cost a lot, but we learned to save money. We start to like the smell of old toys and clothes. We notice smells less as adults. We might smoke, or just get used to it. But the flea market always has a smell. The smell of adulthood is old magazines on a piano. It stays in leather even after washing. Here, we have 3 thrift stores close by. If you start from one end, you can visit two charity stores, a library, a rare book store, and a curio shop. Downtown is full of cars and people every morning. But the thrift store is quiet. No matter how busy the streets, the store is silent. It is a nice place to spend an afternoon. Every year, more cars and people come. They say the city is growing. It has one of the biggest online companies. It still has problems. It reminds me of New York. Everyone is busy with their own goals. People do not ask much from you. You can be alone and quiet. People will not bother you. It is not like the South. There, if you care, you ask questions. Here, people do not pry. You can keep to yourself. The city moves like waves on a beach. It is lively here. The pianist next door and the two singers upstairs keep it lively. We are more like a community than strangers. We help each other. We celebrate birthdays and mourn at funerals. I am lucky to live here. I like my neighbors. They treat me well. I clean up after myself and share food. They do the same. I bring mail to them, and they bring mail to me. It is nice to see them. I think they like me too. I live in a big, modern place. But my neighbors make it feel like home.

I live in a small town in the Midwest, near a big city. My neighborhood is on the east side of town. It is not rich. Houses here do not cost much. Many people rent or own these houses who have low incomes. But the area looks nice and is not bad. My neighbors are friendly. They smile and say hello when I walk by. Crime is a bit higher here than in other parts of town, but not too high. In the past ten years, there were a few violent crimes nearby, like shootings and one killing. Our next-door neighbors lost their son in a shooting outside a bar last year. Our family has only lost a few things from our porch if we leave them out. 

The town has been affected by the "opioid epidemic" in the United States. Many people have died from fentanyl overdoses. But there are many resources to help, like addiction centers and Narcan training for families. Even with these problems, the town has good things. My son's school is great. The principal, teachers, and staff are excellent. My son has special needs but has not been bullied because the school is very positive. He likes it there. The PTO plans many events to involve families and help learning. More than 20% of our town's people are poor, so the school gives free breakfast and lunch to all students. No child goes hungry. No family is treated badly if they cannot pay. School fees, supplies, and trips cost little.

The City Council has improved the town's look. They fixed roads, planted flowers, and repaired parks. Sadly, most changes are in the center and west side, where shops and traffic are. The east side, where I live, is often left out. This upsets people in my neighborhood. 

Overall, I like living in this town. People are friendly. The schools are good. There are enough shops for my family. Our home is not worth much, but it is nice. We have lived here for over 16 years, and we cannot see ourselves anywhere else.

My neighborhood has a lot of culture. It is on a hill, with buildings that have history. I live in an apartment that is seven stories tall. It is across from an old theater. Down the hill is a small arcade bar. Many people go there on warm summer nights. Often, there is a line of people waiting to get in, especially on weekends in June and July. A few blocks up is the city park. It is big for this part of town. The park is surrounded by concrete. There are tall stairs in the wall. In winter, homeless people set up tents along the sidewalk and the steps. It does not snow much, but it rains a lot in winter. The rain makes it hard to stay warm. Keeping their tents close helps them stay warm. They are also near the only family center for miles. They can bathe and shower there. I love my city not just for its historic buildings or architecture. I love it for the culture of the people. Hilltop was once known for gang violence on the West Coast. People still tell stories of those times. The government tried to clean the streets. The people remember. Stories pass from generation to generation. People work hard to keep the area clean, even though it is still considered tough. They care about their city and their block. Some say if you are white, do not walk the Hill after dark. I think this is an old warning, from social conditioning. Maybe I look dark enough to fit in, or maybe Hilltop sees me as one of them. We all know the reminders of racism and fear. Even in a city that is supposed to be a melting pot. No matter where I go, Hilltop is home. I feel alive walking there at night. People offer a jacket more than they rob. It is a place where laundromat owners let me charge my phone to escape the rain. It is a place where, on dark nights, someone might stop, look at me, give me $5, and say I am beautiful and valuable.

I moved to this neighborhood when I started eighth grade. It was hard to make friends at first. But I became close to someone who lived two houses away and another person on my street. They do not live here now, but I still have memories. Most people who lived here then are still here now. My neighborhood is like a normal American suburban area. There are many two-story houses. On warm days, I hear kids playing outside. The neighborhood is quiet most days. I have never had a problem with my neighbors. You are left alone unless you need help. I have ordered many packages and none have been taken from my porch. I trust my neighbors. There is a park a short walk from my house. I have many memories there. I played basketball, football, and baseball with other kids in the neighborhood. I got hurt once when I was elbowed in the nose playing football, but good memories are more than the bad ones. Now, I go to the park with my cousin’s kids. They are younger and like swings and slides. The park makes them happy. The park also makes me remember the past. The neighborhood is very diverse. You can find many kinds of food nearby. Within a mile, there are Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian restaurants. Many people use apps like GrubHub and DoorDash for food delivery. Fast food places are popular and found in most suburban areas. There are also many pizza places. The stores here have everything you need. There are dry cleaners nearby. There is a Walgreens, a CVS, and a Jewel-Osco grocery store on the same street. Some stores are diverse too, like an Indian-owned store. You can buy Indian food there. Overall, I like my neighborhood. Reading on social media and watching the news about bad neighbors makes me grateful for mine.

My neighborhood is near the college I attend. I like living there. There are mostly apartment buildings. There are some restaurants and bars that are fun and not too expensive. One bar was renamed and now costs more, but it is not bad. Most people are nice. They are college students or people with less money because the apartments are cheap. There are many children because there is a school near my apartment. I do not know my neighbors and do not want to. They smoke a lot, so the building put an air freshener near their door. My boyfriend and I think it is funny. The buildings around me are old but may have new insides. Down the street are new apartments. I do not like them because they were not built well. They are expensive to rent. I think this is unfair, but they are close to campus. There is a cheap restaurant five minutes away. They use paper plates and microwave most food. Across from it is a gas station, which is not a good place to work. The city fixed the road last summer. Now there is a nice sidewalk and more grass, so the area looks better. My apartment building has many trees. Some trees were cut down, but there are still many. Behind my apartment is a tree line and more apartments. I live on 42nd street. Behind it is 43rd street, which is not as nice. The sidewalks there are broken. The buildings look shabby. There are many trees, maybe to hide the buildings. Most crime happens at an apartment on that street, but it is not only them. Apartments across from me also have crime and many people move in and out. I like where I live. I can afford it, and many useful places are nearby. The university is close, and there are two bus stops. I can get to the store and downtown easily.

My neighborhood has houses that look like two homes joined together. They are at the end of a street that does not go through. The houses are spread out so they look like single homes. Each house is yellow with white porches and green roofs. Most people are friends. Some nights, we stand at a driveway and talk while children play with toys, draw with chalk, or fly kites. It feels good in this world full of machines and computers. It feels like going back in time. We are near fields and trees with blue skies and white clouds. The bad part? This season, we have tornado warnings. Last night, we heard tornado alarms, so we went to a safe place. I stayed in the bathtub with my small dog, my purse, and some pillows. My big dog would not come into the bathroom. He stayed in the living room, barking because of the strange situation. The neighborhood was quiet except for the sound of big hail hitting the ground. After the storm, the road was steaming because the temperature changed fast. It went from 92 to 75 degrees in minutes. The hail melted when it hit the hot road. I looked up and saw the sun come out as it started to rain. A double rainbow appeared. I ran into the house and got my camera. I took pictures to share with my friends and family online. They were amazed, and so was I. The streets stayed quiet for an hour until people came home after the storm. Then, life went back to normal, with mothers and children outside while dinner cooked. It is a friendly place for someone who moved from New Hampshire to North Carolina. I like the way people talk here. I have a two-bedroom, two-bathroom apartment, just like everyone else. The outside of the houses is the same, but the inside can be different. Some are small. It does not make sense to me. I like to walk in the big field behind my home and go to the pond, which is not for swimming. I have seen deer, and in the morning, you can hear a big frog singing. It is a great place to live, just forty minutes from the city of Charlotte. Each morning, roosters crow from nearby farms. It feels like living in a small village. A donkey at a nearby farm brays at night to let us know he is there. I was lucky to find this nice neighborhood.

I have lived here for about ten years, so I can share what I know. When I first came to my neighborhood, I felt sad. I moved from Riverdale to Stockbridge. I cried because I missed my old home and loved the people there. But my mom and dad wanted the best for me and my little sister. We moved to a better place with good housing and a better high school. Our new neighborhood was not considered "ghetto." 

Over the years, I got used to the new place. I made some new friends and also some enemies at school. I did not get to know most of my neighbors well, except for Mr. Glen and his children, and Dennis, who lived next to us. They are nice people, and I almost think of them as family. I remember going to Mr. Glen’s wedding with my mom, dad, and sister. It was a fun time. I look forward to having my own wedding someday. When Mr. Glen’s wife, Ms. Veda, threw the white strap from her leg, I caught it! I did not catch the flowers, though. We danced all night, and I enjoyed spending time with their daughter, Marsharii. I have not seen her since then. I hope she is doing well now.

The neighborhood is like a maze, but I use a GPS to explore it more. I have gone out with my friends Kason and Curtis. We used to play video games a lot and enjoy life. Sometimes, I go to the park to enjoy nature. It makes me feel calm and at peace. I practice balance with sticks I bought and sometimes use my wooden sword. I enjoy doing things I love. There is a basketball and tennis court here. I have not played in a long time, but it is nice to have them. My dad taught my best friend and me to play tennis with Mr. Graves. We worked hard but always had fun.

I have had many fun times in this neighborhood, and I think the best is yet to come!

My neighborhood is a small town. It is not very different from other towns in South Carolina, but it is important for farming. Johnston is called the Peach Capital of the World. The town sign proudly says this. Most of the land has peach trees or cattle. Houses outside the center of town are far apart. Many are two stories with metal roofs or gray shingles to stay cool in summer. These houses are often not near the road, but farther back with fields in front for animals or crops. In the center of town, there is one stoplight at a four-way crossing. This is where the only stores are. You can get "fast food" at three places: Hong Kong, a small Chinese family restaurant, Fiesta Mexican Restaurant, and Gary's, a small burger place. There was a pizza place, but it closed not long ago. A small pharmacy, Maxwell and Halford Drug, is known for its Cherry Coca-Cola. There is a small, costly grocery store called IGA. It is the only grocery store in town, but people often go to Walmart in Batesburg-Leesville for most of their shopping. The most popular store is Dollar General. It sells many everyday items and is busy all day. There is a small furniture store, Possibilities Furniture & More, owned by a kind local woman. It has been in Johnston for many years and has two movers to deliver furniture. Next to it is a small pet groomer, Clark's Cuts and Kennels. They offer daycare, boarding, grooming, nail grinding, and baths. Both a doctor's office and a vet are outside the center of town. They are small but help the people in Johnston. There is one school, Johnston Elementary School. After fifth grade, students go to middle and high school in the next town. There are no parks, but they are making a new 2.5-acre area for families to enjoy and to attract visitors. There is not much to do here. There are no movie theaters, bowling alleys, places to hang out, playgrounds, pet walking areas, or many restaurants. Even so, it is a nice town. It is so small you might pass by it without noticing!

I live in a small town in Tennessee. It is a suburb area. Our street connects two highways. There is a lot of traffic, but it is a quiet place. Not many people move away or come to live here. I know most of our neighbors. People do yard work and other chores. In winter, we sled on a hill nearby. Our house is at the front corner of the street. We see everyone come and go. We know the cars they drive. If we see a new car, we notice it. Neighbors walk for exercise or walk their dogs. Kids ride bikes and play. We work from home, so we are here a lot. There are four of us: my wife, our two daughters, and me. Our daughters are eleven and fourteen years old. People know us well here. We play outside often, even in the rain. Sometimes we grill on our back deck. The smell is nice. Someone is always cutting grass. You hear lawn mowers from March to October. Our area has many trees. It was once a forest. There is a lot of shade. In Fall, there are many leaves. We rake and burn them. I like the smell of burning leaves. It means Fall is here. Winters are not very cold now. It feels like Fall lasts longer. Our garage is at the back of the house. We use the front door only if someone knocks. That does not happen often. I work on my truck or projects in the garage. When the doors are open, I feel more connected to the neighborhood. On holidays, it is quiet here. At Thanksgiving, families visit. There are more cars then. It is the same on other holidays like Mother's Day and Christmas. I like living here. If it was not a through street, it would be perfect.

My neighborhood is in the middle of the high desert. There is dirt everywhere. People who have not lived here may not know how it feels to see only brown. When you see a green lawn, you know that person pays a lot for lawn care. In the 90s, when I first lived here, houses were far apart. Now there are many new houses, but it is still mostly the same. This place looks more like a city now, but many places are changing like this. Most people here are friendly, but like any city, there are good and bad parts. In my neighborhood, I am with friendly old people, so it is a nice area. The stores here are chain stores like Food 4 Less and Smart & Final. If you want fancy stores, you have to travel. I do not see stores like Whole Foods here. The main jobs in my city seem to be in construction. This is because there is still a lot of open space to build on. I like it the way it is now and do not want it to become too big. I left a big city and do not want to return to that life. I work full-time in construction, as a drywall and T-bar installer. I like the different animals at my home. People come to the high desert for the beauty of the desert. The climate and land here create a special ecosystem. This needs protection and is home to many animals. People living in the high desert should learn about the animals here to live well with them. My family and I get along well with the wildlife. I have three children who love lizards and desert bugs. As I write this, they are outside trying to catch them. We have some attractions here. Victorville is a good place for families to see the desert. It can give you a different experience. Try to visit during the San Bernardino County Fair. The fair will make your visit fun. Nearby, you can go to Wrightwood to see snowy mountains and learn winter sports. Are you interested in the natural history and culture of the high desert? The Victor Valley Museum has old rocks, Native American items, and other things that tell the history of Victorville.

When I talk about my neighborhood, my answer is different. Most people think of houses and streets. For me, my neighborhood is my college campus. The people in my dorm are my community. The campus area around is also part of my neighborhood. My neighborhood is like a normal neighborhood in some ways. It has houses, people, stores, and parks.

Let me talk about the "houses" first. There are three kinds of houses here: apartments, real houses, and dorms. In the apartments, 2-4 people live in each room. Each floor has 4-6 rooms. Most buildings have two floors. So, about 20 people live in each building. The real houses can be rented by people who are part of the school. They have 2-4 bedrooms, mostly for alumni. There are not many of these houses because they are not efficient. Dorms have hundreds of students. Usually, two students share a room. Dorms are the most common housing here.

Next, I will talk about the people. My school values diversity. People from all cultures and ages live here. Staff live in the houses. New students stay in dorms. Older students live in apartments.

Now, let's talk about stores and parks. My school is like its own neighborhood. It has many stores and one park. The stores have food and school clothes. You can find everything you need here. The park is a place for everyone to play. It is clean and safe because everyone takes care of it.

There are not many sidewalks where I live. Everything goes downhill, and my house is at the top of the steepest hill in the area. People call it the "work out hill" because many joggers run up it each day. Since there are no sidewalks on my street, everyone walks on the road. The road has holes in some places and can be a bit hard to drive on. Some of the wires for telephone and electric look old and worn. It rains and storms a lot here, so branches and other things often hit the power lines. The many repairs make the wires look patched up. There are many tall evergreen trees everywhere. But people here do not like the trees. They try to cut down as many as they can because the trees block the view of the ocean. That is why many houses are high on the hill, with big glass windows to see the bay. It is beautiful at sunset when the water seems to light up and the sky turns orange. It is often cloudy, so you mostly see the sun through a haze. Most days are cloudy and wet. Moss grows on everything: roofs, cars, and railings. I once left my car in my driveway for a month, and when I went to use it, it was green with moss. It took me three hours to clean it off. There are not many children where I live, even though there is a school a few blocks away. Most people in my neighborhood are older and many are retired. Instead of kids, people have dogs. It is common to see them on lawns or running down the street. If you leave a door or window open, dogs might come into your house. I found one in my living room once and had to make it leave through the front door. Rabbits run wild here. Some are big, and gardeners do not like them because they dig up plants. My cats love them and have chased most away. We also have birds like sparrows and hummingbirds, and sometimes a hawk or eagle flies by until the crows chase it off. There are no stores nearby, but if you walk downhill to the waterfront, there are a few restaurants with fresh seafood. There is not much of a beach, but the rocks along the shore are fun to throw into the water. The bay is not very wide. You can see the other side clearly even through the mist on most days.

If you want to visit Bensonhurst, Brooklyn, it is easy to find. Public transportation in New York City is very good. Bensonhurst is a city neighborhood, so it feels like you are still in New York City. You will see many Asian stores in the area. In the last 20 years, many Asian people have moved to Bensonhurst. You will see an Asian-owned store on almost every block. Supermarkets and laundromats are very popular. People like these stores because they have good food, low prices, and are easy to reach. Near my place, there are four Asian supermarkets within a short walk. This makes getting groceries easy. Bensonhurst is not only Asian. It is a mix of many people, including immigrants and their children. Most big businesses are Asian-owned. There is also a park nearby with basketball courts, a large field, handball courts, swings, a playground, and a water fountain for kids. Parks in New York City are very mixed, with people from many backgrounds playing together. There are not many big office buildings here. You will find co-op and condo apartments. Most homes are two-family houses. People here are nice but can be loud. You often hear loud music from cars on the street. If you visit at night, be careful. The area is mostly safe, but you might meet people who cause trouble. I was bullied here long ago, and there are package thieves. Also, many people do not clean up after their dogs, even though there is a fine. You will see dog waste on the street every morning. Be careful not to step in it and keep your shoes clean!

The first thing to know about Portland, Oregon is the word "weird." The city's unofficial slogan is "Keep Portland Weird." It is written on the back of a building that is a pizza place, bar, music spot, and strip club. Some people think this slogan means to remember the Portland of the 90's and early 2000's. At that time, Portland was less known and less costly. It had many creative and unique groups. To others, the slogan invites people to come to Portland, where being called weird is now a good thing. Even though many wealthy people from California have moved here, and many new condos are built for them, Portland is still weird. Weird does not always mean accepting, but it means accepting things that are not usually accepted. Weird does not mean we do not have modern things and modern problems. Like the rest of the country, we buy most things from China. There are many ways to be weird, to be not normal, but Portland also has normal things. Portland has yoga, hipsters, and business people. Maybe weird means we take all this less seriously. In my neighborhood, as in many Portland neighborhoods, we have colorful houses and home gardens with flowers, herbs, and vegetables. In the summer, we have free boxes. Free boxes are usually cardboard boxes with things someone does not want anymore, but they can be plastic bags or boxes too. They often hold clothes and books but can have anything. The magic of finding a treasure just right for the person walking by is what Portland is about. That is what Portland means to me, but I am just one type of weird among many. Some people here would never think of picking their clothes from a box on the street. Those people go to goat yoga (yoga with real goats) or Timbers soccer games. Portland is full of people who like many different things. It is full of people who follow dreams or think about dreams while spending too much time at the bar. Yes, Portland has a drug problem. Drug problems often come from mental health problems. The constant rain and gray clouds may add to this. Portland also has a homelessness problem. No one seems to know what to do about it. The homeless come here for social services, which are better than in most places, but still not enough. People who are not homeless feel both care and dislike. In this, we are not weird at all.

The mountains are always there. They are to the north. They see the sun rise and set. I may forget them because of work and life, but they do not change. On days when I am very stressed, they ask me to see them. When I do, they help me find peace. They give me strength to go on, one day at a time. I moved here when I started college. The mountains north of the campus first caught my eye. The university has pretty buildings, ponds, and trees. But the mountains are what I love most. The town is also nice. There are many cafés where I studied hard. I can walk or take a bus to downtown. There, the old bricks of restaurants and offices give a feeling of history. This town can be as busy as a big city. But it is also calm and quiet. After a few blocks, I can leave the busy area by going past the library. This mix of different places makes the city special and exciting. It is easy to make many good memories here. I remember walking by the park with friends or running downtown to see a movie with tickets from the university. There are also hard memories, as in any place. The ponds are good for thinking or crying late at night. I know this well. I watch turtles, ducks, and insects live their lives. I wonder about my purpose. I walk past the pond, the park, and small houses. I reach a main street. The sun shines on the palm trees and the sky. I see the sunrise and know I am walking north. The mountains are there, as always. They touch the sky more than any building. They remind me to keep going.

At first, you might not notice it. It is a place behind shops, where you do not think people live. But if you walk past the old Whole Foods and the empty hotels that are busy only in summer, you will find a busy area. Here, there are many apartments. They are next to each other like a row of dolls. The first apartments have been on the news for bad things, so we will not talk about them. But the other apartments are different. Across from them is a small part of a community college. Students come here in the morning with coffee, yawning as they start their day. Cars wait as the students enter, and drivers get upset when there are many students. The road meets another road by a park and a place where people heal from broken bones. The healing place has nice chairs and a fan that moves the warm air. Children play in the park. They run and do tricks, while bees fly around flowers. Old people walk their dogs and look at the teenagers on skateboards. There is a sushi place by the park where food is cheap. Next to it is a swimming store and a nail salon. You can do many things here at once. There is also a frozen yogurt shop where teens hang out. They eat yogurt and do tricks on skateboards. This neighborhood is a picture of America in the quiet south, where things do not change much.

My neighborhood is interesting. Most houses are for one family. Some homes are split into two, but they are still attached. My home has a small yard in front and a small driveway on the left. It looks like many others here, reminding you of when the suburbs were the American dream. This dream once was strong in this country, but now it is not as strong. Still, my neighborhood and others like it remain. They show that the dream is still alive, and we hold onto it as best we can. People do not feel as hopeful as before. The yards are not kept as well, but there is still a car or two in every driveway. Children play as if this place is their whole world. The public school has been here for almost 90 years. It still stands, giving hope to the young and memories to the older people. There are few churches, mostly empty, but the basketball courts are full. All homes look different but feel the same. There is a big supermarket called Super "A". It is owned by a large Yemeni family, maybe the only Arab family here. Most people are African American. The streets are wide, and children play football, stopping only to let cars pass. Many people have lived here for generations. They can tell stories of when everyone knew each other. There was a karate school, but when karate movies stopped being made, kids lost interest. Now it is a pharmacy because, as they say, drugs make everything better. There is also a small movie theater that plays old movies at a low price. Young people do not go there much because they want new movies. Older people like it because it is cheap and peaceful. An expressway goes through our town, but the exit and entrance are in the next town. There was once a request for an exit here. Young people wanted it, but older ones did not. They said it would ruin the town, and they convinced the city council to say no. A new high school is being built, and we are choosing a mascot. I think a cyborg with a country accent and a log cabin would best show what my town is like.

I live in a big city, and my neighborhood has many different kinds of people. Homes are spread out between places for business. Many kinds of businesses are here. Some have offices, while others are stores, places to eat, or places for fun. There are always new places to eat or shop. Some stores are big and well-known, but small shops are also liked. These shops are in malls and along streets near homes. These streets make the area busy, but parks are also nearby. People often go to parks with their children.

My neighborhood has many kinds of people. There is a strong LGBTQ+ group, an Orthodox Jewish group, and people from the former Soviet Union. Outside my neighborhood, there are more people from different places. The city has places like Korea town, China town, and Little Armenia, not far away. But driving a short way can take a long time because of traffic, especially during busy times. Few people walk in my city. The city is large, and most people do not like to walk far. So, the traffic is very bad, and parking is hard to find.

There has been a lot of building in recent years. Many big apartment buildings are being added. The city is popular, but some people do not like more people and cars coming. There are many kinds of homes here. Not all people want to live in big apartments. There are houses, small apartment buildings, and condos. Some places have single-family homes, others have duplexes. This is true in my neighborhood, so there are many choices for homes. People here are of all ages. I do not know most of my neighbors. It is not a close community now, but I remember playing outside with friends when I was a child.

“Where is everything?” she asked as we drove past the corn fields. The fields seemed to go on forever. “This is it!” I said. I knew she would be surprised by how open the land was. She came from a town where the grocery store was a short walk from her home. She had never seen this much open space before. Seeing all the corn fields, I told her about growing up in rural Ohio. In that moment, she understood who I was and where I was from. 

We drove down a small country road. We passed a quarry with water in it. Just past it is where I live. The houses are made of brick and stucco. Each house has at least half an acre of land around it. Everyone takes pride in their yard. In spring, many flowers bloom. The trees change with each season. The driveways are filled with luxury cars that shine in the sun after a wash. 

As we got closer to my grey stucco home, we saw my Korean neighbor. He is always outside with a friendly smile. He spends the day mowing his lawn and sings while he works. Everyone enjoys his singing. He is a nice person with a special history. He used to be a doctor. Now, he blends in with the grass on his mower. 

Then, you reach my home. In the side yard, there are many geese. Our Terrier chases them. Out back, there is a small stream that leads to the quarry. You can hear bullfrogs, the stream, and cows from nearby farms. Across a wooden bridge is a place with trees, herbs, and wildflowers. I spent much of my childhood there. We built tree forts and chased animals. There was always something to do with friends. 

Winters in my town can be very cold, but they are also beautiful. The yard turns from green to white. The trees look bare. When it snows, everything is covered in white. My sister makes snow angels and snowmen. We often fought as kids. In winter, we had snowball fights. We built forts with branches. In our snowy world, we played pretend and nothing else mattered. We were just kids having fun.
